<sn><md>### Crust{.text-center}

The **crust** is the Earth's outermost solid layer. It is thin compared to the other layers and forms the Earth's surface, including continents and ocean basins. The crust varies in composition and thickness.

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* **Continental Crust**

  * Forms the continents.
  * Thicker (30–70 km) and less dense than oceanic crust.
  * Mainly composed of granitic rocks rich in silica and aluminum (SIAL).

* **Oceanic Crust**

  * Forms the ocean floors.
  * Thinner (5–10 km) and denser than continental crust.
  * Mainly composed of basaltic rocks rich in silica and magnesium (SIMA).
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![diagram](https://www.shutterstock.com/image-vector/continental-crust-oceanic-3-dimensions-260nw-1497339509.jpg)
:::
:::

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* **SIAL** : Refers to rocks rich in **Silicon (Si)** and **Aluminum (Al)**, characteristic of the continental crust.
* **SIMA** : Refers to rocks rich in **Silicon (Si)** and **Magnesium (Mg)**, characteristic of the oceanic crust.
:::

