</md></sn><sn><md>### Mantle{.text-center}

The **mantle** lies beneath the crust and extends to a depth of about 2,900 km. It is composed of silicate rocks rich in iron and magnesium and behaves as a solid that can slowly flow over long periods.

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* **Upper Mantle**

  * Extends from the crust to about 670 km deep.
  * Partially molten in some areas, allowing tectonic plates to move over it.
  * Includes the **asthenosphere**, a semi-fluid layer that facilitates plate motion.

* **Lower Mantle**

  * Extends from 670 km to 2,900 km deep.
  * Denser and more rigid than the upper mantle.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![diagram](https://as2.ftcdn.net/v2/jpg/05/04/35/79/500_F_504357965_CRhgULoEFX0YTtK7JcXyu5XMc7aSn4Tz.jpg)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Lithosphere

The **lithosphere** is the rigid outer layer of the Earth, including the crust and the uppermost part of the mantle. It is broken into **tectonic plates** that float on the underlying asthenosphere.

### Asthenosphere

* The **asthenosphere** lies below the lithosphere in the upper mantle.
* It is semi-fluid and partially molten, allowing the lithospheric plates to move.
* Plays a critical role in plate tectonics, volcanic activity, and earthquakes.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Core{.text-center}

The **core** is the innermost layer of the Earth, composed primarily of iron and nickel. It is divided into two parts:

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
* **Outer Core**

  * Liquid layer extending from 2,900 km to 5,150 km deep.
  * Responsible for generating the Earth's magnetic field.

* **Inner Core**

  * Solid layer extending from 5,150 km to the Earth's center at 6,371 km.
  * Extremely dense and hot, with temperatures reaching up to 5,700°C.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![diagram](https://images.nagwa.com/figures/explainers/216173989151/4.svg)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Summary

The Earth’s structure can be summarized as concentric layers:

| Layer             | Subdivision          | Characteristics                                                               |
| ----------------- | -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Crust**         | Continental, Oceanic | Solid, thin, less dense (continental), dense (oceanic), composed of SIAL/SIMA |
| **Mantle**        | Upper, Lower         | Semi-fluid (upper), rigid (lower), silicate rocks rich in Mg &amp; Fe             |
| **Lithosphere**   | –                    | Rigid outer layer including crust and upper mantle                            |
| **Asthenosphere** | –                    | Semi-fluid part of upper mantle allowing plate movement                       |
| **Core**          | Outer, Inner         | Outer: liquid, generates magnetic field; Inner: solid, very dense and hot     |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Important Definition

| Term                | Definition                                                                                                                                            |
| ------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Magma Chamber**   | A large underground pool of molten rock located beneath the Earth's surface.                                                                          |
| **Magma**           | Molten rock beneath the Earth's surface, which can solidify to form igneous rocks.                                                                    |
| **Lava**            | Molten rock that reaches the Earth’s surface during a volcanic eruption.                                                                              |
| **Crater**          | A bowl-shaped depression at the top of a volcano formed by volcanic activity.                                                                         |
| **Caldera**         | A large, circular depression formed when a volcano collapses after a major eruption.                                                                  |
| **Hot Spring**      | A natural spring where heated groundwater emerges from the Earth’s crust.                                                                             |
| **Asthenosphere**   | The semi-fluid layer of the mantle below the lithosphere that allows tectonic plates to move.                                                         |
| **Fault**           | A fracture or zone of fractures between two blocks of rock, along which movement has occurred.                                                        |
| **Fold**            | A bend in rock layers caused by compressional forces in the Earth's crust.                                                                            |
| **Tectonic Plate**  | A large, rigid piece of the Earth's lithosphere that moves over the asthenosphere.                                                                    |
| **Plate Tectonics** | The scientific theory explaining the movement of Earth's tectonic plates and resulting phenomena like earthquakes, volcanoes, and mountain formation. |
